<TITLE> Support for Japan's 6-month-old govt slips further </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TOKYO, Mar 16 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Support for Japanese Prime Minister Yukio Hatoyama's government has more than halved since it took power six months ago, a poll showed on Tuesday in a further sign of trouble for the ruling party ahead of an election expected in July. Hatoyama's Democratic Party swept to power on Sept. 16 after a historic win in an election for parliament's powerful lower house, but since then voter support has slid to 32 percent from initial highs over 70 percent, the poll by the Asahi newspaper showed. It was down from 37 percent from the previous month. The disapproval rate has risen to 47 percent from 14 percent last September. Other voters polls by domestic media have shown a similar trend as doubts persist over Hatoyama's leadership and ability to make tough decisions on the economy and diplomacy, with voters increasingly disaffected by a series of funding scandals involving ruling party lawmakers. The Asashi survey showed 30 percent of just over 2,000 respondents said they would vote for the Democrats in the mid-year election for the upper house. The Democrats aim to secure an overall majority in the upper house so they can to pass bills smoothly without relying on two small coalition partners. In the survey, 67 percent said the change of government last year, which ended half a century of almost unbroken rule by the conservative Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), was good for Japan. The main opposition LDP has failed to gain much support since the last year's election defeat, with only 21 percent saying they would vote for 
